What is Semantic HTML?
Semantic HTML means using HTML tags that describe the meaning of the content, not just its layout.
Instead of using many generic <div> elements, HTML provides tags that tell the browser and developers what the content actually represents.

Example:
              <header>Website Header</header>
              <nav>Navigation Menu</nav>
              <main>Main Content</main>
              <footer>Footer Information</footer>


Why Semantic HTML is Important
1️⃣ Better readability for developers
When someone reads your code, they immediately understand the structure.
Example:
Using divs
                        <div class="header"></div>
                        <div class="menu"></div>
                        <div class="content"></div>
                        <div class="footer"></div>
Using semantic HTML
                        <header></header>
                        <nav></nav>
                        <main></main>
                        <footer></footer>
The second one is much clearer.

2️⃣ Better for SEO (Search Engines)
Search engines like Google understand your page structure better.
For example:
<article> → blog post
<nav> → navigation menu
<main> → main content
This helps search engines rank content properly.

3️⃣ Better for accessibility
Screen readers used by visually impaired users rely on semantic tags.
Example:
A screen reader can jump directly to navigation if <nav> is used.

